        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>Eastern European Renaissance-Baroque ceramics styles [300107027], Eastern European Renaissance-Baroque styles [300107026], Renaissance-Baroque regional styles [300112572], Renaissance-Baroque styles [300021033], Renaissance-Baroque styles and periods [300021031], European [300020656], styles, periods, and cultures by region [300111079], Styles and Periods (hierarchy name) [300015646], Styles and Periods Facet [300264088]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Refers to the style of pottery made by peasants in Hungary and Moravia (Czech Republic) from the late 16th through the 17th centuries. It features vigorous and stylized flowers, animals, and figures applied to characteristically globular short-neck jugs and plates with a wide flat ledge.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Se refiere al estilo de cerámica fabricado por campesinos en Hungría y Moravia (República Checa) a fines de los siglos XVI hasta fines del siglo XVII. Ofrece flores lozanas y estilizadas, animales y figuras aplicadas a jarros característicamente globulares y de cuello corto y platos con un reborde liso ancho.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Verwijst naar de stijl van het aardewerk dat werd gemaakt door boeren in Hongarije en Moravië (in het huidige Tsjechië) van de late 16de tot het einde van de 17de eeuw. De stijl wordt gekenmerkt door krachtige en gestileerde bloemen, dieren en figuren, aangebracht op typische bolvormige kruiken met korte hals en borden met een brede, platte rand.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>指西元十六世紀末葉至十七世紀，匈牙利和摩拉維亞（捷克共和國）農民製作的陶器風格，特以活力且風格化型的花卉、動物和人物圖案裝飾在球形短頸壺與口緣寬平的盤子上。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
